Obese baby's menu: doesn't eat sausages and dinners
More than a third of children 9 to 13 years of age have overweight problems, with 9 percent of schoolchildren overweight and 5 percent of children obese.
Obese children usually come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as the current survey showed.
Once again, it shows how important it is for a healthy development of a person’s environment in which he grows up and the patterns that surround him.
For example, sausages appear half as often on the tables of obese children as in normal - weight families.
Fried fries had for dinner the day before the research related to an educational event called Obesity is not a coincidence of more than 19 percent obese.
In fat families, it is also not customary to play sports, but this applies to most of the families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of the children replied that their parents will find time to move actively at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place at the end of last year's school year and was attended by nearly 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of Obesity is not a coincidence supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 schoolchildren from the 4th to 8th grade have been involved in the project.
The correct diet and exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
"Only half of the respondents said, for example, that they eat five times a day in breakfast-dinner-dinner-dinner-dinner mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites of proper nutrition," one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and no sausage at night
Experts point out that even relative details, such as regular family breakfast times, are essential to healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing was finding out that in a tenth of the households, you don't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
A questionnaire showed that the families of obese children consume unhealthy fries more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly, their parents had less than half - 15 percent.
Build your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own menus according to their own tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"The popularity of sweet lemonade is particularly alarming," says the final survey report.
At lunch as the main dish, pasta won just above the poultry.
However, the children practically did not want legumes at all and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetables is low.
Adaptation to Health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In many cases, there was a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," says the project's results.
For example, it was marked with sweet lemonade, where more children would have preferred ordinary water.
Children have also checked poultry and fish as the main meal of the day in the questionnaire much more often and would limit sweet meals and dumplings.
