In Need for Speed: The Run is raced across America.
Review
Originally, a carefree ride is transformed into a routine morning shift trip due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Ambition was largely accomplished, but it is of no use when no one seemed to want to do anything extra.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run raised high expectations before the release.
He promised that the old race series Need for Speed would once again move a bit in a new direction and from playable demonstrations appeared to be a game that would not be in the genre of action racing just to number.
We were also curious to see how the embedded passages would end up in which the main hero would get out of the car and run on his own.
However, as is the case with the NFS series, many results are a little different than we expected.
They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less years.
So it's not really mistakes, it's more of a kind of incomprehensible laziness of developers.
Adventure begins very well.
You are introduced into a story whose main hero Jack has certain personal issues and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You'll get behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco, and your job is to be the first to arrive in New York.
The idea brings with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't get the feeling that the game is always the same.
Some of the environments are also very pretty to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-class.
But driving across the desert, autumn landscape or high in snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
Moreover, from time to time, races are varied by an uncharacteristic element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you must be careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
In addition, individual races are quite well placed in a row.
There's only a few types, but it's enough.
For a while you are trying to overtake the desired number of opponents (actually classic race), then you are catching up again (classical fight with stopwatches) and then there is a duel waiting for you with only one opponent.
Police will also get involved in this from time to time, which makes your efforts even more difficult.
New is the passages outside the car.
It's more of an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by printing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
But they will be surprised that these passages are in play much less than you would expect (in particular perhaps only three).
But in the end it is for the benefit of the thing, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of the above mentioned, it ranks among the elements that augment the game.
The ride model follows in the footsteps of previous parts.
This means that it is certainly no longer anything these days, but it cannot be said that it is a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the more active racing of the local driving model still suits quite well, even though we could find better in the competition.
So far, everything's in perfect order.
However, problems begin to emerge after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer in order.
We don't expect this type of game to count complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave before any impact on any object, then I guess everything's not all right.
Typically, when you drive over or pass cars in normal traffic, you sometimes lick each other easily, but sometimes in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even go straight for it.
The reboot system doesn't seem to bother you at all, but it will make you feel better.
The reboots are designed so that if you smash or drive far off the track, the game will throw you back at the last clue point on the track.
But there are only five reboots available in each race.
When you run them out, you have to start the race all over again.
So it's more of a tool in case something goes wrong than if you could rely on it.
Sometimes reboots don't help, however, it solves the need to learn a given section of the race by heart.
The big problem with the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can't fit in.
Other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or one minute later.
It will piss you off especially in situations where you can see the opponent passing easily between two opposing cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you get there, because it's "counted" so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
Throughout the game, you will find several places where you, again regardless of the time, always overtake the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
The opponent must get there in front of you at any cost, apparently.
When it's ahead of you, it's getting worse for you to look at the cars, so at first, you're probably going to have a couple of smashes.
It is possible to understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenalineier, but the performance is so obvious that it reliably quickly disgusts you.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes so actionful that sometimes you can't quite watch where things fly.
And it doesn't really matter whether the concept of 50 unique tracks, the gearing of the races, is responsible so that boredom doesn't stand a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to switch cars during the race.
You have to watch out for gas stations near the roads, because that's where you can change the car, although in most cases you can get by with what you have right now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sport cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars on straight highways and exotic supercars for technical riding, for example on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and mode of challenges, which are races in individual locations, which you know from the story.
Here you receive not only medals, but also experience points into your profile, which is common for both challenges and story.
Various items are unlocked to gain a higher level of driver: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for profile.
It is also linked to the online Autolog function, which compares your achievements with other players and provides other community functions.
One other difficult to understand is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can get to the subway tunnel (but so be), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (but so be).
On the tachometer, the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (let's be) flash, and in that direction, the subway line comes crashing in and scrapes you uncompromisingly.
In the editorial office, we can probably still for a few days talk about whether nobody really gave a little thought when creating the game, or whether the authors think we're really that big of an idiot.
The technical aspect of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It is so saddened that, in some tenser moments, the imagery decreases, in some cases rather tragically.
However, it is mainly about accidents with more participants, when continuous imaging would not be of any use to you anyway.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of the younger audience, a soundtrack from the "every dog in a different village" category was created, but it is possible to assume that someone will not just buy the game for listening to music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so greatly embarrassed.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of the NFS in the last few years.
But this is how the game looks unfinished.
I'm sure it's fun, but get ready for mistakes to blow your eyes out with the power of airport spotlights.
