The IBM Innovator begins the second century of its existence
If someone were looking for a word that would best express IBM's strategy, the closest would probably be "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, yet it has been a hundred years since its founding.
The foundation of this longevity was laid by the first head of the company, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already stamped a password that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became a print around which the life of the future giant (and also the name of the internal magazine, which began to be published in IBM in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully built corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because she remained faithful to her basic values and was not afraid to change everything else around her.
This allowed us to transform technology, business, and society during our first centuries.
We hope that we can achieve even more in the second hundred," said Samuel J. Palmisano, current director on the anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson treated his employees in the 1930s, like the entrepreneur Bata in the Czech Republic - people from IBM had paid holidays as one of the first American employees, employer insurance plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system to reward the best inventors and traders.
The IBM has a long-term relationship with the customer.
