How the price of tours developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
At that time, travel agencies in the vast majority sold only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus travelled for a holiday to the sea in the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Society in Crimea near the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both towards the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime inclined towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within socialist countries.
If the citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union for example, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual way was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered tours to the West at the time, but it was necessary to stand in line overnight with sleeping bag or to have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Still, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the trip to the West.
By far, however, the Czechs most often spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this custom survives to this day.
Traveling by Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While the holiday in GDR or Bulgaria was our maximum until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel to the most popular Croatia since it was part of Yugoslavia until 1989.
Right from the early 1990’s, visa requirements were lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, which triggered a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czech trips slept in tent parks, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was the carriage of own food, cans, salamis, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely exchangeable Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally purchase the Western currency after many tens of years.
However, our standard of living and, with it, our average salaries were rising, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have regularly started to prepare charter flights since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper because of the possibility to negotiate quantity discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free contact with virtually all developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when thanks to considerable demand he was sent from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exotics, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm distant countries, this winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US cancelled visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person for one foreign holiday, including the cost of their stay.
