Massacre at a personal level
An emotionally strong new book by Peter Englund called Beauty and Grief: The Confidential History of World War I (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War) begins with such a long list of performers that your head spins.
One piece of advice on how to behave at that moment: Carefully tear this page out and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know all of you in the Englund novel, and this list will serve you as a navigation - as a beacon - at times when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite fittingly, as an "antihistorical work".
It contains several well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, almost lacking ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, rather than a "book about what it was like", mainly about "feelings, feelings, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and sorrow" combines the experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women in war, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botany to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy or die.
Their lives are shimmering like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fate, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classic historical novels.
It alters the idea that World War I was just about the fearsome trench fighting on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bee nests falling on them, spending Christmas in the shadow of pyramids or struggling with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, it is a very touching reading.
War consumes people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts to sound in the distance, and you're the woman who's home with her kids, run away or stay?
Who's this coming from?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the entire war was unleashed.
"Vakuum arising from lack of facts," observed Mr.Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from CVs, letters, and other already published material.
The descriptions of their lives may sound both frightening and engaging, but thanks to the inclusion of tiny moments and details, they are absolutely alive and believable.
Many of them discuss suffering and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Replacements, substitutes everywhere."
"Coffete substitute, aluminum imitation, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It refers to "meal made from pressed rice cooked in mutton fat (and supplemented with false wood bone), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato skins, wooden soles".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
