The walls have eyes: how scientists examine you on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July murderous rage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public hearing.
Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was certainly not lonely in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - just go on Facebook.
"We realized that finding them is actually not so hard," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of the recently published report by the British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, says Bartlett that it was enough for scientists to simply use the site’s advertisements and, thanks to this, with complete precision, identify the demographic group – something that marketing workers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups, then they focused their attention on them and sent them ads. However, instead of inviting them to the newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire that asked questions about their level of education, their relation to violence and optimism in view of their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from over 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online followers of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are irritated by the growing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with their offline activism are more sensible, democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything, from health problems to social trends that hide status updates, posts on walls and pressed "I like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them provides three different data daily, making this social network literally a "information supernova" that is behind the development of many new researches. The number of academic works in which the word Facebook is known has risen to almost 800% compared to five years ago.
For some scientists, the Facebook spell is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to harass them on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to do a survey among the British National Party people, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side where they'd never let you go," Bartlett says.
"All this Facebook is breaking down - you're just going straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken Facebook appearances were much more at risk of alcoholism than those who were silent about the subject.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem cannot be solved if you cannot diagnose it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Health, Behaviour and Development of Children at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise not have a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The site's information team has compiled statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day, electoral participation in 2010 and the National Satisfaction Factor (mainly using the information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long claimed that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the site.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most users ever thought that scientists could look at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, on a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it that information was just between them and their friends."
Subsequently, it is also important to consider the question of methodology.
Even when research is offline, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
