New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately disproved by unquestionable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of using the funds of his campaign to try to conceal his illegitimate affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that fell past Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
It's crawling with stories of cheating at school and college.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many scams are we dealing with?
Studies show that in one day, you'll lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers had lied three times during the first ten minutes of their first encounter in life.
Determining lies, or "recognising lies", is a necessary skill for everyone, for personal or professional reasons.
But it is not a social game that is similar, let's say, to Sharon, when one cries out, "I have you." Recognizing deception is a serious sector of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're squirming, stuttering, blushing, or squirming.
But do not conclude that it is somehow difficult to spot and detect liars.
The trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from the sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from an extensive and emerging sector on the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help to you in today's difficult world - especially if your work responsibilities include hiring, holding interviews, negotiating or managing people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them be vigilant, direct their emotions, and intuitively appreciate how the other side accepts them.
From research we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women say more lies "focused on others" - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (but the lies they say are usually "unspeakable").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's normal behavior.
It's called initial observation.
Thanks to him, he'll have later findings to compare them to.
Notice the subject's posture, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone routinely taps his feet constantly so that you don't wrongfully accuse him of lying just because he starts to tap his feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and non-verbal behavior.
But consider this only as a warning signal, not as proof of a lie.
People who tell lies can stop moving the upper half of the body when they try to remember their fictional story, turn the toes of the shoes to the door, lean towards the exit, significantly change their posture, or show "relief after the interview" - excessive relief and change of position when confession is difficult behind them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over just to see what a relief it will look like after the interview.
Also feel the subject’s language.
The famous story is how Scott Peterson once misrepresented himself and used his past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which triggered a nationwide search for her body.
Deluded individuals may also express themselves in a measured manner: "I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky" or they will repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal characteristics are very slight.
Someone can use a lot of "melting tongue" to answer the difficult question, "Well... to tell you the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
We don't know much about such an answer, and it's often another warning signal.
There is no spell to reveal every lie, but it is possible to master the skills to stalk a lie.
With these skills, one will have a better chance of not falling for a liar and a cheater in his personal and professional lives.
