The appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that is holding this country at the brink of economic disaster and that has put the entire eurozone in danger.
The Presidential Palace issued a report stating that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the President with the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti explicitly did not say that he would be able to create a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of creating a government in less than three days, much shorter than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to combat the political and financial crisis, which led to the level of debt rising to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough package of austerity measures required by European leaders, which is the only way to restore Italy's compromised credibility.
Due to the instability of the markets, interest on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity of 7 percentage points exceeded the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for rescue.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers' organization Confindustria, told journalists after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much".
We believe that this government is the last option for Italy to get out of this pressing situation.
