The new Monti government must have strong support from Parliament in order to promote unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in a given effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure and warns that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monti started negotiations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organisations on Monday.
The round closes on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by the President of Napolitan, who made it possible to move very quickly in response to the crisis.
After a short drop from the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, the interest on Italian bonds returned to a critical line, responding to the uncertainty that the new Prime Minister would succeed.
Saving Italy, whose public debt amounts to 1.8 trillion euro, would be beyond the scope of current eurozone financial reserves.
