Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jacome presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor’s secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Communications and Transport Secretariat (SCT) reported that the results of the accident investigation, in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven others died, show that the helicopter landed directly on the terrain with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt forced landing.
At the Dionisio Pérez Jacome press conference, the Communications and Transport Secretary, said that before the start of the aircraft the pilot stated that the climate conditions allowed the flight.
"Parts that appear suggest that the unit has come into contact with the terrain several times, the wings are entangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull".
It also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, therefore it met all requirements for the transfer of personnel.
In addition, it stated that no components were found on the ground following an investigation carried out in the field of impact.
"The search revealed that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft crashed into the mainland as integral.
"The helicopter was intended for 19 people, it met all requirements for the transport of persons.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, managing director of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that it was a routine overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At the press conference, SCT Deputy Pérez Jacome listed six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to visual flight rules, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
The AICM reports indicate adequate launch conditions, according to which the aircraft moves towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds the crew searched for a lower area and greater visibility up to the valley of Cuernavaca.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter are identical, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight trajectory prior to the impact.
Dissipation of aircraft residues in restricted territory:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a flat trajectory and from the side.
A diagram of the dissipation of the remains of the aircraft indicates that the helicopter was complete at the time of the impact on the mainland.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence of an explosion or fire at the scene of the accident.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During the field work were found the remains of the aircraft at a height of 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloped, the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage of the likely collapse along the route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter could have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search around the accident, in a territory that is more extensive than the area of designation, no remains of the helicopter were found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still solid.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has begun research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts research in order to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research entitled "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Teens" allows to obtain results on overweight.
In a report by the head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 21st century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and pupils of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre of Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
People can also participate in research, with or without permission. People can come to participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where every Saturday from 8 o’clock will be tested for minors.
He stressed that research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and since 8 October this activity is also carried out at the Zahualcóyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to track down risk factors on Mexican children and young people and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined every Saturday, and genes are examined (try to identify genes involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health care workers’ concern over the alarming increase in child weight.
'The health surveys carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was only a 77% increase in obesity among boys and 47% increase in girls. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight," said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators was the assumption that the population of the country differed from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetics, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that general obesity genetics are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus establishing whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the probability that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-sugar conditions.
So far, the information is confidential, it is handed over in writing to the parents and explained to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life that means a lack of daily physical activity, a day’s sitting in front of television, and the use of means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Overweight also causes large caloric intakes, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in Asphalt from UNAM.
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalt with polymers and creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If paving was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each period of rainfall in the Valle de México Metropolitan Region, Rafael Herrera Najer, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction of potholes, or even could be completely removed.
In his lecture, the technological cause of the potholes he gave during the International Year of Chemistry announced that the laboratory under his direction develops modified asphalt with polymers, which should create a mixture with similar characteristics as asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of oil, is the formation of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a large molecular mass called asphalt, and others with a low molecular mass called mortars. Together, they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of the asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, alerted the expert on chemical engineering.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is an asphalt liner, made up of small stones embedded in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the insert is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to decompose well.
If it were modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, he thinks a chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer, called the cloak, consisting of fine stones, is placed on the asphalt insert, i.e. sand also embedded in the asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and ensure friction of the road.
As a part of the paving, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to bear in mind. In particular, water has a large impact on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads in and it is hard to get out, it causes softening of all layers of paving and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the construction of potholes, the first film of the casing will be damaged and only then will the asphalt liner be damaged. However, it does not occur at one moment, but it is a slow process that should stop at the first signs using suitable maintenance programmes.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tiles must correspond to the load of vehicles and it must be ensured that this load will not be exceeded.
