Nord Stream, the new port of entry of Russian gas into Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and led down the Baltic Sea has begun to work.
They must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated in Nord Stream’s inauguration, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte have jointly turned the control around the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas will start to flow to Western Europe every year with the first 1 224 km pipeline connecting the region of St Petersburg with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomora.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is the quantity equivalent to the whole of French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom early completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being led on the ground by a third State (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing somewhat of their power: the possibility of pushing Russia through threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", with an appeal to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying that it is a subject politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created cracks between Europeans from east and west.
Russia has barely been able to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries with high gas consumption, whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us", confirmed François Fillon during the opening ceremony of this pipeline and demonstrated the point at which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The undersea pipe is made of steel with a concrete casing to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the time of World War II.
"For the sake of security, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations at all.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were not eager to see the Russian state society permanently settled off their coasts.
"In case of a malfunction, we stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute", explains Jens Müller.
In case of leaks, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by builders, for welds were designed to create leaks once every 100,000 years.
An offshore pipeline is controlled by a boat-drawn submarine robot, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device circulating inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 metre is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is pushed with gas.
In the finish line, it will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts over three whole days of journey at 3 m/s.
The long-distance pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
Circulation of gas is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, who holds a 51% stake, remains the leader.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transport capacities to the company for five years, which may be renewed.
"Gazprom will have a profit from the total capacity, whatever the quantity of the actual gas being transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez group, investment costs thus increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will come back to them, because Gazprom alone takes the risk.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves at 4.5 meters high form the exit gate of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
