Why is the unemployment rate of handicapped workers so high?
Around 19% of handicapped people are looking for work.
Today opens 15. Week for employing handicapped people.
Despite the voluntarist public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed handicapped people is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it daunting?
"No, underscored by Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, who organizes Week for employing handicapped people."
"The progress achieved in 15 years is remarkable."
"At the time, the percentage of unemployed was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that there are numerous obstacles to unemployed disabled people before their entry into work.
These are elderly: 37% have more than 50 years (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% of them do not graduate, and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are handicapped.
Finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for handicapped versus 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to employment and which represent the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are unspoken ways of thinking that certainly evolve, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité Association found that the questioned managers have a "weak level of knowledge about handicapped people" with "an exaggerated idea of people in a wheelchair and psychological or mental deficiencies".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the objective of employing 6% of handicapped workers as set out in the 1987 Law.
The last known numbers, which date back to 2008, indicate the status of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, responsible for collecting fees from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof is the number of " fined" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 provinces to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euro).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large businesses."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of businesses with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of businesses with 100 to 199 employees.
